Architecture plan for Issue #19: Base the daily reading on Vancouver local time instead of UTC

Current project shape
- Browser-only React + TypeScript + Vite SPA.
- Domain logic is kept in small modules under src/domain/:
  - elements.ts: Element enum/type plus deterministic date-to-element logic.
  - trigrams.ts: Trigram enum/type plus deterministic date-to-trigram logic.
  - guidance.ts: element-to-palette/fabric guidance data.
  - themes.ts: trigram-to-theme data and motifs.
  - reading.ts: blended reading generation.
  - dateKey.ts or equivalent date helpers should own any calendar-day normalization.
- UI composition lives in src/components/ and src/App.tsx:
  - Header/date summary consumes the daily reading model.
  - Color palette, mood/theme, and blurb sections render data produced by domain helpers.
- Tests use Vitest and should cover deterministic date behavior independently of the browser's local timezone.

Issue dependency and implementation plan
- Issue #19 depends on the existing date-based Element and Trigram calculation from prior issues.
- The change should be centralized in the shared date helper/model creation path, not duplicated in UI components.
- All daily calculations and displayed date labels should use the same Vancouver calendar day.
- Tests should simulate UTC instants around Vancouver midnight and UTC midnight to prove the app changes day at America/Vancouver midnight, not at UTC midnight.

Key design decisions
- Use the IANA timezone identifier America/Vancouver through Intl.DateTimeFormat, avoiding hardcoded UTC offsets because Vancouver observes daylight saving time.
- Keep Element/Trigram mapping deterministic by converting an instant to a Vancouver YYYY-MM-DD key before calculating day index/cycle position.
- Accept Date inputs in pure functions for tests; production code can call new Date() once and pass that instant through the same helper.
- Avoid server code, database state, or per-user locale/timezone behavior. The requirement is global Vancouver local time for every user.
- Ensure the rendered date, Element, Trigram, palette, mood, accent, and blurb all derive from the same Vancouver date key to prevent mixed-day UI near midnight.
